{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659270"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:04:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:04:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20860"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20860"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97376"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13735"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20860"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79991"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12679"},{"type":"tags","id":"12680"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33058"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33059"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97376"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EClass II Major Histocompatibility Complex (MHC) molecules play a crucial role in the adaptive immune system by presenting peptides to helper T cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the structure-function relationship of Class II MHC molecules?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Polymorphism in \u03b12 and \u03b22 domains determines peptide binding specificity","Peptide-binding cleft formed by \u03b11 and \u03b21 domains determines antigen presentation","CD8 binding site on \u03b22 domain facilitates interaction with cytotoxic T cells","Invariant \u03b1 chain paired with polymorphic \u03b2 chain creates peptide specificity","Covalent disulphide bonds between \u03b1 and \u03b2 chains stabilise the heterodimer"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EClass II MHC molecules are essential for presenting extracellular peptides to CD4+ helper T cells. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epeptide-binding cleft formed by \u03b11 and \u03b21 domains determines antigen presentation\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because these domains create the peptide-binding groove and contain most of the polymorphic residues that determine which peptides can be bound and presented.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymorphism in \u03b12 and \u03b22 domains determines peptide binding specificity\u003C/strong\u003E - The \u03b12 and \u03b22 domains are primarily structural and do not determine peptide binding.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECD8 binding site on \u03b22 domain facilitates interaction with cytotoxic T cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Class II MHC molecules interact with CD4+ helper T cells, not CD8+ cytotoxic T cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInvariant \u03b1 chain paired with polymorphic \u03b2 chain creates peptide specificity\u003C/strong\u003E - Both chains contain polymorphic regions that contribute to peptide binding specificity.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECovalent disulphide bonds between \u03b1 and \u03b2 chains stabilise the heterodimer\u003C/strong\u003E - The chains associate through non-covalent interactions.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClass II MHC molecules are expressed mainly on professional antigen-presenting cells including dendritic cells, macrophages, and B cells. The polymorphic nature of the peptide-binding region allows for presentation of diverse peptide antigens, enabling broad immune surveillance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Class II MHC molecules are heterodimers composed of \u03b1 and \u03b2 chains that present extracellular antigens to CD4+ T cells.","The peptide-binding cleft of Class II MHC molecules is formed by the \u03b11 and \u03b21 domains, which is where most polymorphism occurs.","Class II MHC molecules are primarily expressed on antigen-presenting cells and interact specifically with CD4+ helper T cells."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; page 199."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79991"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20860"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79991"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T13:21:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T13:22:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13735"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97376"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11595"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diseases of the immune system","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":5,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:55:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:55:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/126